 as killers and thieves, and as the victims of crime. Like the civil pleas, the crown pleas illuminate the workings of the common law, but in addition they illustrate the functions and purposes of local and central government, shedding light in sometimes vivid detail upon the lives of the humbler members of society, upon their occupations, relationships, misfortunes and quarrels - and the sometimes bizarre ways in which they met their deaths. The eyre was led by William of York, the King's justiciar and later bishop of Salisbury, and his colleagues who met at Ipswich, Cattishall (outside Bury St Edmunds) and Dunwich. The eyre roll, now in the National Archives, is the first from Suffolk surviving in full to have been edited and published; it has the particular interest of coming from a county that was then one of the most populous and prosperous of English shires.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Apr 2024) 4aBritish Local History. 4aMedieval History. 7aHISTORY / Medieval.2bisacsh  aEast Anglia.  aattacks.  adeath.  aditch.  afratricide.  ajustice.  alaw.  amurder.  aponds.  arivers.  arobbery.  asuicides.1 aGallagher, Eric, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aSummerson, Henry, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSummerson, Henry, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertBoydell and Brewer Complete eBook-Package 2021z978311143100040uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781800103436?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781800103436423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781800103436/original  a978-3-11-143100-0  Boydell and Brewer Complete eBook-Package 2021b2021  aGBV-deGruyter-alles